Washington today is charged with artistic excitement. Attracted by the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, internationally celebrated theatre, opera, and ballet companies, symphony orchestras, and soloists visit it regularly.

It is difficult to remember that when the Center opened in 1971, with Leonard Bernstein's famous "Mass," Washington was a near-wasteland in aesthetic terms. The Center has been the prime force in transforming the city into a cultural mecca that rivals New York, London, and Paris
